- Glycine (as the amino acid unit without the R group) typically has a melting point well over 200 °C due to strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding.
- An ester linkage generally has a lower melting point than the corresponding acid due to the lack of strong hydrogen-bonding. Ethyl acetate, a simple ester, has a melting point of -84 °C.

Thus, the addition of the phenyl group to glycine should significantly increase its melting point due to an increase in molecular weight and rigidity, but the ethyl ester will introduce flexibility and reduce the possibility of hydrogen bonding, lowering the melting point comparably. Assuming benzene increases the melting point by about +50 to +60 °C over the base ester due to rigidity, and the glycine unit could essentially raise it by a similar amount but is counteracted by the ethyl ester.
